---
import DashboardLayout from '@/layouts/Dashboard.astro';
---

<DashboardLayout>
  <article class="max-w-3xl leading-relaxed">
    <h2 class="mb-4 text-xl">About VulnTrends</h2>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      VulnTrends is an open-source project that tracks trends in vulnerability
      patching across major software manufacturers. The dashboard visualises
      vulnerabilities discovered, fixed, the time between discovery and patch,
      and vulnerability backlogs — all over time, with the ability to filter
      by manufacturer and switch between monthly and yearly granularity.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Methodology</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      Data is drawn from publicly available security advisories and
      vulnerability databases. Each source is fetched, normalised to a common
      schema, and aggregated into time-series data for visualisation.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      Where multiple sources report the same vulnerability (identified by CVE
      ID), vendor-specific advisory data is preferred over the NVD/CVE record,
      as vendor advisories typically provide richer patch-timing information.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Data confidence</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      The "Time between discovery and patch" chart can only be calculated for
      CVEs where both a discovery date <em>and</em> a patch date are known.
      Most vendor advisories only publish a patch date, not a separate
      discovery date — the chart only shows the subset of CVEs with full
      data. This can over-represent vendors that publish more detail (e.g.
      Mozilla, which reports explicit Reported/Fixed timestamps), and
      under-represent vendors that don't.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      The "data confidence" badge on the patch lag chart shows what fraction
      of records have both dates, and the "Hide low-confidence manufacturers"
      toggle filters out vendors whose data is too sparse to be meaningful.
      Cross-vendor comparisons should always be interpreted with this
      asymmetry in mind — a 0-day median patch lag usually means
      "missing discovery data", not "instant patching".
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Data sources</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      The pipeline currently ingests data from the following sources.
      "Direct" means the project runs a parser against the vendor's own
      advisory feed; "NVD-backed" means we get the coverage from NVD's
      CPE-based vendor queries (no live parser, but the timeline metadata
      is what NVD exposes for that vendor); "stub" means a parser slot
      exists in the pipeline but is currently a no-op awaiting an
      upstream-API upgrade.
    </p>

    <h4 class="mt-6 mb-2 text-base font-semibold text-vt-text-secondary">Direct feeds</h4>
    <ul class="mb-4 pl-6 space-y-2 text-vt-text-secondary list-disc">
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Mozilla</strong> — Mozilla Foundation Security Advisories (MFSA JSON feed).</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Microsoft</strong> — Security Response Center (MSRC) CVRF API. The parser uses per-vulnerability <code>RevisionHistory</code> dates to recover each CVE's true first-disclosure date rather than the catalog-wide <code>CurrentReleaseDate</code>. <strong>Mariner documents are filtered out</strong> at the parser — MSRC also publishes a per-distro catalog for Mariner (their Linux distribution) whose CVEs are upstream Linux entries (kernel, glibc, OpenSSL, …); without the filter, every re-import of that catalog would spike the <em>Vulnerabilities discovered</em> chart with thousands of non-Microsoft CVEs dated to the import moment. The filter is documented in <code>scripts/pipeline/sources/msrc.ts</code> and has a regression test in <code>scripts/pipeline/test-msrc-mariner.mjs</code>.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Google Chrome</strong> — Chrome Releases blog (Blogger's Atom JSON feed). HTML scraping is unreliable for this page (ad-network redirects), so the parser consumes the structured feed instead.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Apple</strong> — Support articles on <code>support.apple.com</code> (the <code>gb-table</code> index, since the legacy <code>HT\d+</code> URL pattern is gone).</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Palo Alto Networks</strong> — <code>security.paloaltonetworks.com/json</code>.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Fortinet</strong> — PSIRT page at <code>fortiguard.com/psirt</code>; separate Published and Updated dates give a real patch-lag signal.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Adobe</strong> — <code>helpx.adobe.com/security.html</code> index + best-effort per-bulletin CVE fetch (rate-limited; the per-CVE detail step is a graceful-degradation path, not a guarantee).</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 class="mt-6 mb-2 text-base font-semibold text-vt-text-secondary">NVD-backed vendors</h4>
    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      These manufacturers don't currently expose a usable public advisory
      feed (or we haven't wired one up yet), so the dashboard's coverage
      for them comes from NVD's vendor CPE queries. You get
      <code>discoveredDate</code> from the CVE's NVD <code>published</code>
      field; missing <code>patchedDate</code> shows up as a "missing
      discovery data" gap on the patch-lag chart — see the
      <em>Data confidence</em> section above.
    </p>
    <ul class="mb-4 pl-6 space-y-2 text-vt-text-secondary list-disc">
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Oracle</strong></li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Samsung</strong> — no public advisory programme before 2013.</li>
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Google</strong> — NVD's <code>google</code> CPE vendor covers Chrome and Android-family CVEs that the Chrome Releases feed doesn't capture.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 class="mt-6 mb-2 text-base font-semibold text-vt-text-secondary">Stubs (no live data today)</h4>
    <ul class="mb-4 pl-6 space-y-2 text-vt-text-secondary list-disc">
      <li>
        <strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Project Zero</strong> — parser slot
        reserved. The old Monorail endpoint
        (<code>bugs.chromium.org/p/project-zero</code>) returns HTTP 404
        after Google's migration to <code>issuetracker.google.com</code>.
        Until the parser is upgraded, Project Zero coverage flows in via
        NVD's <code>google</code> query. We're missing PZ's Reported/Fixed
        timeline metadata specifically.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Cisco</strong> — parser slot reserved.
        The legacy OXML feed is
        deprecated and the openVuln API requires OAuth credentials from
        the Cisco API Console. Coverage today comes from NVD's <code>cisco</code>
        query; we're missing Cisco's own patch-timing
        data specifically.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-vt-text-primary">OSV</strong> — opt-in. Returns
        data only when the <code>OSV_LOOKUP_CVE_LIST</code> environment
        variable points at a CVE-ID list. The pipeline ships with no
        list configured, so this source returns <code>[]</code> on a
        default run.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4 class="mt-6 mb-2 text-base font-semibold text-vt-text-secondary">Cross-vendor backbone</h4>
    <ul class="mb-4 pl-6 space-y-2 text-vt-text-secondary list-disc">
      <li><strong class="text-vt-text-primary">NVD/CVE</strong> — National Vulnerability Database. The canonical CVE feed the project leans on as both a backbone (gap-filler for vendors we don't parse directly) and a record-level cross-source validator (the <code>SOURCE_PRECEDENCE</code> map in <code>scripts/pipeline/normalise.ts</code> prefers vendor advisories over NVD when both report the same CVE).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Limitations</h3>

    <ul class="mb-4 pl-6 space-y-2 text-vt-text-secondary list-disc">
      <li>
        Discovery dates are not consistently available across all sources.
        Where a discovery date is unavailable, the advisory publication date
        is used as a proxy, which yields a 0-day patch lag (likely
        misleading — see the data confidence section above).
      </li>
      <li>
        Patch dates are only available when the source explicitly reports them.
        NVD records do not include patch dates.
      </li>
      <li>
        Backlog figures represent vulnerabilities that have been discovered
        but not yet patched, based on the dates available. The aggregator
        applies a 5-year stale horizon: a vulnerability with no recorded
        patch date and a discovery older than 5 years is assumed to have
        been patched silently and dropped from the backlog. Without this
        horizon, a manufacturer with sparse patch data would appear to
        accumulate an ever-growing open backlog. The horizon is
        configurable via the <code>BACKLOG_STALE_YEARS</code> env var.
      </li>
      <li>
        Apple advisory data is scraped from HTML pages and may be affected by
        structural changes. When scraping fails, Apple-related CVEs from NVD
        are used as a fallback.
      </li>
      <li>
        The "Vulnerabilities fixed" chart counts records with a patch date.
        This is a reasonable proxy for "fixed" but may include records where
        the patch was a no-op or the vendor advisory covered multiple CVEs.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Coverage eras</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      Vulnerability data is split into two coverage eras. The dashboard
      defaults to the full-coverage era (2013+) because the data from
      earlier years is opportunistic — many manufacturers had no public
      advisory programme before 2013, and NVD's CPE-based vendor matching
      was immature.
    </p>

    <ul class="mb-4 pl-6 space-y-2 text-vt-text-secondary list-disc">
      <li>
        <strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Full coverage (2013–present)</strong> —
        All 10 manufacturers have advisory programmes and NVD CPE coverage
        is mature. Charts over this range are cross-vendor comparable.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="text-vt-text-primary">Partial coverage (1999–2012)</strong> —
        Data exists but is incomplete and not cross-vendor comparable.
        Visible when you select "Full history" in the range selector.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Data integrity</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      The pipeline runs a series of semantic checks on every dataset via
      <code>npm run data:audit</code>. These checks surface (but don't
      block) issues like future-dated records, CVE-year mismatches,
      per-source year-over-year outliers, per-manufacturer patch-date
      coverage gaps, and a dedicated <strong>catalogue-re-publication</strong>
      check (A6) that flags any record whose <code>discoveredDate</code>
      falls in the last 18 months but whose CVE-year is at least 2
      years earlier — the signature of an upstream "we just re-imported
      our historical catalog" artefact that produced the misleading
      MSRC spike through 2024-Q3. A6 hard-errors the build if it
      triggers, so a regression in the parser filter or the dedup
      merge fails fast rather than silently producing a chart with a
      month of fabricated data.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      The dedup merge (which combines vendor and NVD records into a
      single canonical record per CVE) is gated on a CVE-year sanity
      check: a candidate <code>discoveredDate</code> more than 1 year
      from any CVE in the record's <code>cveIds</code> list is treated
      as an upstream artefact and discarded. When both candidates fail
      the check the record is dropped entirely. The logic and the
      Mariner filter both have dedicated regression tests; run
      <code>npm run data:test</code> after any change to
      <code>scripts/pipeline/normalise.ts</code> or
      <code>scripts/pipeline/sources/msrc.ts</code>. The
      <a href="/analyst-guide" class="text-vt-accent hover:underline">analyst guide</a>
      has more detail on the date-selection rules.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      Every record carries a <code>provenance</code> field capturing
      when and from where it was fetched, so individual data points can
      be traced to their source for citation and drift detection.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Snapshot archive</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      Each successful pipeline run writes a copy of the raw data and
      metadata to <code>data-archive/&lt;YYYY-MM-DD&gt;/</code>, along
      with a SHA-256 manifest in <code>data-archive/manifest.json</code>.
      The archive acts as Tier-2 retention: if a future parser regression
      defeats the silent-empty safeguard, the archive provides a
      known-good dataset to restore from. Old snapshots are pruned by
      <code>npm run data:prune</code>: daily for the last 90 days,
      monthly (1st of month) for the previous 5 years, yearly thereafter.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Neutral framing</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      This project presents data as-is, without editorial annotations or
      interpretive labels. Users are encouraged to draw their own conclusions
      from the visualised trends.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Licence</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      VulnTrends is open-source software released under the MIT licence.
      The aggregated data is derived from publicly available sources and is
      provided for informational purposes.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-8 mb-3 text-lg text-vt-text-secondary">Who is behind this?</h3>

    <p class="mb-4 text-vt-text-secondary">
      VulnTrends is the work of <a href="https://github.com/robpomeroy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Rob Pomeroy</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</DashboardLayout>
